    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <placeName>Mt Sterling Ill</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <del>
                    <date>Aug</date>
                </del>
                <date>Sept. 6 1866</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <addressee>Mr Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Walnut Street</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Pa</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Dear Sir <hi rend="indent(1)"><sic>Dear Sir</sic></hi></p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Your kind letter<lb/> of <date>Aug 29</date> is received and I
                send<lb/> enclosed ten dollars for a <sic>coppy</sic> of your<lb/> Bible of that
                price: I thought it could<lb/> come by <sic>male</sic>; but I suppose that
                express<lb/> would be a better way; and it <sic>payed</sic> on<lb/> delivery; I live
                    <sic>onely</sic> a mile from our; or<lb/> the Depot.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In my last letter to you<lb/> I did not expect to <sic>clame</sic>
                your attent-<lb/>ion beyond a casual remark in regard<lb/> to my desire to know your
                views of the<lb/> fore part of <persName>Isaiah</persName> Ch. 42.</p>
            <p>Should you stop to write to all of your<lb/> patrons as you have to me it would<lb/>
                be a tax beyond endurance: I can there-<lb/>fore with greater propriety
                    <sic>appretiate</sic><lb/> it, as coming from a friend deserving<lb/> extra
                respect and esteem, and especially<lb/> as it was <sic>writen</sic> in an inferior
                condition<lb/> of the body. You appear to be<lb/> strong in the expectation of the
                restoration<lb/> of <placeName>Israel</placeName>; but I suppose that neither
                your<lb/> faith or desire is greater than mine; for shou<lb/>ld I know it false or
                    <sic>disbeleave</sic> it I should<lb/> be perfectly be fogged in all my
                religious views</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>When I hear the solicitation and the ardent<lb/> desire to some of the Jews
                    <sic>neare</sic> the old<lb/> Temple at <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>
                exhibited saying<lb/> How long, How long, O lord Shall we<lb/> yet <sic>wate</sic>,
                it fines my life with that symp-<lb/>athy and desire they have.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Although I am a <sic>beleaver</sic> in Christian<lb/>ity as I
                    <sic>understant</sic> it I am confident that<lb/> the chance of the Jews is far
                preferable<lb/> to the <sic>profesed</sic> Christian.</p>
            <p>But the <sic>meanes</sic> that God intends to make<lb/> use of by which to
                    <sic>rase</sic> mankind to the<lb/> highest form of Civilization, is a
                question<lb/> that deserves <sic>studey</sic>, thought and reflec<lb/>tion. I have
                for a long time<lb/> been well convinced that nothing<lb/> short of a
                    <sic>compleat</sic> Theocracy is sufficient<lb/> for the task. One Language one
                Law<lb/> One Religion and One Capital<lb/>
                <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>. But this is by no means<lb/> an answer to the
                question for the fulfill<lb/>ment of these realities involve the requi<lb/>site
                necessity of the commencement of the<lb/> Resurrection of man. This I admit is<lb/>
                the grand suspect to the <sic>studed</sic>: for certain<lb/> I am that through faith
                and practice<lb/> will it <sic>onely</sic> come and in due time from the<lb/> hand
                of God. I mean a resurrection<lb/> into immortal life.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">With great Respect</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">Abel Larkin</persName>
            </p>
            <p>PS I am sorry to say that I was scarcely<lb/> competent to read your letter</p>
        </body>
